  "prompt": "What is the difference between machine learning and deep learning?",
  "response": "Machine learning and deep learning are both subsets of artificial intelligence (AI), but they differ in their scope and approach to solving problems.\n\nMachine learning is a broad category of AI that uses algorithms to learn from data and make predictions or decisions. It can be further divided into subcategories such as supervised learning, unsupervised learning, and reinforcement learning. Machine learning algorithms can learn from labeled or unlabeled data and use statistical methods to make predictions or find patterns in the data. Some common applications of machine learning include fraud detection, recommendation systems, and image classification.\n\nDeep learning, on the other hand, is a subset of machine learning that focuses on neural networks with multiple layers. These layers are used to extract and transform features from the input data, allowing the algorithm to learn complex representations of the data. Deep learning algorithms are typically trained on large amounts of data and require significant computing power. Some common applications of deep learning include speech recognition, natural language processing, and computer vision.\n\nIn summary, the main difference between machine learning and deep learning is that deep learning is a specific approach within machine learning that uses neural networks with multiple layers to learn from data. While machine learning can be used for a wide range of applications, deep learning is particularly well-suited for tasks that involve large amounts of data and complex pattern recognition.",
